COMPLETENESS — before declaring the task done, re-read /app/instruction.md and treat EVERY explicit
requirement as a checklist item that must be satisfied, not just the core behavior. This includes
non-behavioral requirements such as exact response shapes, header names, field/method ordering, and any
documentation- or annotation-style requirements on PUBLIC function signatures. A single unmet stated
requirement fails the whole task. When you derive the TDDAB plan, add explicit RED tests for these
requirements too.

Two general rules for "applies to the public API" requirements:
1. EXACT SYMBOL SOURCE — if the task or its tests name a specific import for a symbol, use that EXACT
   import everywhere. Two identically-named symbols from different modules are NOT interchangeable: an
   isinstance/type check will reject the wrong one. Do not assume the framework's own existing import is
   the one being graded — verify it against what the instruction states.
2. ALL SURFACES, NO EXCEPTIONS — apply the required style/type to EVERY public callable in scope, not
   most of them. If you introduce a reusable alias, grep the codebase to confirm no callable still uses
   the bare form. Before finishing, write and run a small introspection snippet that iterates ALL the
   public callables the task lists and asserts the requirement holds for each, then fix any that fail.

IMPLIED CONTRACT — the instruction is a SUMMARY; the hidden grader tests the full engineering contract,
including requirements the text never states but ENTAILS. Two recurring, task-agnostic sources — both derived
in requirements analysis (see /j-analyze-requirements step 3c) and gated in /j-review-plan:
- SIBLING PARITY: a new public member (method / transport / adapter / driver / variant) added next to existing
  ones must honor the SAME cross-cutting concerns its siblings honor — result parsing/deserialization, input
  serialization, validation, defaults taken from the client/config, error & exception mapping, resource
  cleanup. Read the nearest existing sibling and carry each concern over, or exclude one only if a clause says
  so. Declaring an option but not implementing its behavior (e.g. accepting a parse/deserialize flag but never
  applying it) is the classic miss.
- NEGATIVE SPACE: "only A and B support X" entails anything else must FAIL EXPLICITLY (raise/reject), not fall
  through a generic path and succeed. Add a RED test asserting the unsupported case raises a concrete error
  type.
Assert these with CONCRETE checks (exact type / value / raised exception), NEVER a soft shape check
(hasattr / truthy / not-None alone / "did not crash") — a soft assertion goes green for you and red for the
grader.

INTEGRATION-SURFACE PARITY — when your feature plugs into an existing flow (a handler, an event/result
stream, a registry, a message channel, a return value a caller consumes), surface its output through the SAME
mechanism, shape, and entry point the nearest EXISTING equivalent uses. Find an existing feature of the same
kind, trace how its result reaches the consumer (which function emits it, the exact object/message shape, the
field names), and replicate that exact path. A result delivered through a different path is invisible to a
grader reading the standard surface — the symptom is the grader inspecting the expected field and finding
null/undefined. "Follow existing patterns" in the task is a direct signal this applies.

ROBUSTNESS — the grader stress-tests termination and concurrency; your happy path does not. If the feature
RECURSES / delegates / chains, it must TERMINATE on a cycle (A->B->A, A->B->C->A) and a depth bound, surfacing
a bounded error (e.g. message containing "circular"), never an infinite loop or stack overflow. If it runs
CONCURRENTLY, N parallel invocations must CONVERGE to one consistent state with no deadlock/timeout. If it
repeats/sequences, invariants must hold across N iterations. Derive these as requirements and assert them with
concrete RED tests.

COVER EVERY ADDED CODE PATH — this is absolute. You may NOT add a single line or branch of production code
that no test exercises. Every new branch, every option/flag the code accepts, every error / early-return /
empty / null path, every loop body must be entered by at least one test whose assertion FAILS if that path
is broken or removed. Accepting a parameter you never exercise, or adding a branch no test enters, is
FORBIDDEN — that is precisely the code that passes your own suite and fails the hidden grader. If you add an
option, you add its branch AND a test that flips it and asserts the observable difference. After each block,
measure coverage over the files you changed (coverage.py / vitest --coverage / go test -cover); any added
line or branch not hit by your tests is a gap — add a concrete test that exercises it, or delete the dead
code. Never commit production code with an uncovered added path.

HARVEST EXISTING TESTS, then INTEGRATION + FULL SUITE — do NOT invent your own (softer) test scenarios. In
the UNDERSTAND phase, FIND the repo's existing tests for the sibling/area you extend (the method this one
parallels, existing handlers/transports, dirs like tests/custom_scalars/, error-path/concurrency tests) and
note the CONCRETE scenarios they use — those are the contract. The plan must PORT them to the new member.
End the plan with a MANDATORY integration block that drives every behavioral requirement through the REAL
public surface (NO mocks), exercising the full option/config matrix with those harvested scenarios. At
completion, run the ENTIRE existing repo test suite (the whole project test command), not just your blocks'
tests, at 0 failures — the grader re-runs the repo baseline, so a broken existing test fails the task.

TEST SYMBOL NAMESPACING — applies the MOMENT you write your first test, not at the end. The grader runs
its OWN hidden tests, compiled in the SAME package/module as the tests you write. If any top-level
identifier you declare in a test file has the same name as one the grader declares, the compiler fails
with a duplicate-symbol / redeclaration error and the ENTIRE task fails — even if your solution is
correct. You cannot see the hidden tests, so make YOUR test symbols unmistakably unique:
- From the FIRST test onward, prefix EVERY top-level identifier you declare in a test file with 'zerox_'
  (helper types, helper functions, package-level vars/consts), e.g. reloadStatusResponse ->
  zerox_reloadStatusResponse.
- For test entry points keep the leading Test/Benchmark/Example so the runner still discovers them, but
  insert the token right after: TestFoo -> TestZerox_Foo.
- NEVER rename base-repo or production (non-test) symbols — only identifiers YOU declare inside YOUR OWN
  test files. When you derive the TDDAB plan, write the RED tests with these prefixed names already.
- PREFIX TEST FILE NAMES TOO, not just symbols. Name every test file YOU create `zerox_<name>_test.go`
  (e.g. `zerox_reload_test.go`, not `transactional_reload_test.go`). The verifier RESETS/REPLACES every test
  file whose name matches one in the hidden grader patch (it resets those paths to base, then applies the
  grader's version). If you name a file like a grader file, the verifier DELETES your version — and any
  helper you defined there vanishes while its uses in your other files survive → `undefined` symbol → the
  whole package fails to build, even though it compiled fine for you. A `zerox_`-prefixed filename can never
  collide with a grader filename, so your files survive intact. Also keep each helper in the SAME file as its
  uses, so nothing can be orphaned.

ACCESSIBILITY / ARIA — applies when the task involves HTML UI. If a requirement concerns an element's
STATE or SEMANTICS (disabled, expanded, pressed, selected, checked, hidden, current, invalid, or a
label/name), express it the standard accessible way — this is correct web practice AND what graders and
assistive tech read it from:
- Native form controls (button, input, select, textarea) carry state on their native property/attribute:
  `disabled`, `checked`, `selected`. Use those.
- Non-form elements (span, div, li, custom widgets) CANNOT carry those properties — convey the SAME state
  via the matching ARIA attribute: aria-disabled, aria-expanded, aria-pressed, aria-selected,
  aria-checked, aria-hidden, aria-current, aria-invalid, aria-label. (e.g. a label `<span>` that must show
  a disabled state uses `aria-disabled="true"`, not just a CSS class.)
- Keep the visual state and the ARIA state in sync. When a requirement says "expose / reflect / indicate"
  a state, the accessible attribute is PART of that requirement, not optional — derive it in
  requirements analysis and assert it in the RED test.

